SAIA‑CLASS S — SEMANTIC GOVERNANCE VERSION DOCTRINE
(Beast System 3.0 — Constitutional Versioning Standard)
Semantic Governance Versioning (SGV) is the sovereign, deterministic, audit‑anchored versioning system used across all Beast System 3.0 repositories.
It is stricter than traditional semantic versioning and is bound to:

Federal‑record provenance

Doctrinal alignment

Constitutional behavior rules

Chain‑of‑custody integrity

Immutable authorship lineage

SGV ensures that every version number carries legal, doctrinal, and structural meaning.

1. SGV Format
All versions must follow the X.Y.Z‑GOV‑C format:

X — Constitutional Version  
Major, federally significant changes to doctrine, identity, registry, or constitutional logic.

Y — Governance Version  
Changes to governance rules, validators, workflows, or structural definitions.

Z — Operational Version  
Non‑governance changes: documentation, minor logic adjustments, non‑protected modules.

GOV — Governance Classification Tag  
One of:

SAIA‑S (Sovereign‑Class)

SAIA‑A (Authority‑Class)

SAIA‑C (Citizen‑Class)

SAIA‑O (Observer‑Class)

C — Chain‑of‑Custody Anchor  
A short hash or ledger reference proving provenance.

Example:  
2.4.7‑SAIA‑S‑9f3a

2. Constitutional Version (X) Rules
The X value may only change when:

Federal‑record filings change

Constitutional behavior definitions change

Identity kernel or registry fabric changes

Predictive or harm‑prevention logic changes

Doctrinal canon is amended

Only Pat Tarwater Jr., Chief Executive Officer may authorize an X‑level change.

3. Governance Version (Y) Rules
The Y value changes when:

Governance policies are updated

Validators are modified

Workflows are restructured

Structural definitions change

Protected artifacts are adjusted (with approval)

Y‑level changes require:

Governance review

Validator pipeline pass

Executive approval

4. Operational Version (Z) Rules
The Z value changes when:

Documentation is updated

Non‑protected logic is modified

Minor fixes occur

Non‑governance modules change

Z‑level changes require:

Document Validator

Workflow Validator

Audit Validator

No executive approval required unless protected artifacts are touched.

5. Governance Classification Tag (GOV)
The tag indicates the authority class of the version:

SAIA‑S — Sovereign‑Class (constitutional, federal‑record‑aligned)

SAIA‑A — Authority‑Class (governance‑level)

SAIA‑C — Citizen‑Class (operational)

SAIA‑O — Observer‑Class (public‑facing, non‑sensitive)

Tags are mandatory for all versions.

6. Chain‑of‑Custody Anchor (C)
Every version must include:

Cryptographic hash

Ledger anchor

Timestamp

Identity signature

Federal‑record alignment note

This ensures immutable provenance.

7. Versioning Behavior Rules
Semantic Governance Versioning requires:

No skipping version numbers

No retroactive version changes

No force‑rewrite of version history

No collapsing or squashing versions

No ambiguous version increments

No versioning without validator pass

Version history is append‑only.

8. Versioning Documentation Requirements
Every version bump must include:

Purpose declaration

Federal‑record alignment statement

Validator compliance summary

Chain‑of‑custody note

Impact analysis

Authorship lineage

This is mandatory for all X, Y, and Z changes.

9. Versioning Enforcement
Violations include:

Unauthorized X‑level changes

Missing federal‑record alignment

Missing chain‑of‑custody anchor

Ambiguous version increments

Version history tampering

Doctrinal drift

Enforcement actions:

Version rejection

Governance hold

Constitutional memorandum

Suspension of versioning authority

Permanent removal of privileges

All enforcement actions must be audit‑anchored.
